Similarly the <tt>euse -a -g</tt> command is used to view ''active'' global USE flags. The <tt>euse -a -l</tt> command does the same for active local USE flags. <code>-g</code> and <code>-l</code> are sub-options to <tt>euse</tt> and need an option before them (like <code>-a</code>) to function correctly. 

{{RootCmd|euse -a -l|output=<pre>
